<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="172" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,152,503]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,188,215]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: SVL Min/Max (14.68/ 
<quantity box="[582,702,188,215]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.568" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" unit="mm" value="35.68">35.68 mm</quantity>
); midbody scales 41–47 (x̅ 43.6); males with elevated number of escutcheon scales (~95); ten toe lamellae on the fourth toe; males with marked lineated head pattern; males with marked reticular pattern; scapular patch reduced to a midcentral rectangle, and ocelli located on the periphery of the patch; scapular patch in contact with nuchal spots (
<bibRefCitation author="Padilla, L. F." box="[722,869,296,323]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" refId="ref21580" refString="Padilla, L. F. (2006) Geographic variation in color pattern on Sphaerodactylus macrolepis Gunther 1859, (Sauria: Gekkonidae). M. Sc. Thesis, University of Puerto Rico, San Juan. 153 pp." type="book" year="2006">Padilla 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,152,503]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,342,332,359]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">Color in life</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[357,442,332,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="20.[151,250,992,1017]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,730,962]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1435,722,972]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 22. Live specimens of Sphaerodactylus g. spanius. A, female from Toro Negro, Puerto Rico. B, male from Divisoria, Puerto Rico." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3587001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3587001/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
): Female: ground color light brown to straw, head and tail orange to light gray, head pattern well defined, medial lines separated and parallel, ocelli color white, or sometimes gray (
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A." pageId="21" pageNumber="172" pagination="193 - 260" refId="ref23344" refString="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A. (1966) Sphaerodactylus (Gekkonidae) in the greater Puerto Rico region. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 10, 193 - 260." type="journal article" year="1966">Thomas &amp; Schwartz 1966</bibRefCitation>
). Male ground color light brown, head and tail orange. Iris color yellow, green, brown, copper, or golden.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
